com.mewna.catnip.extension

Interface Extension

  • All Superinterfaces:
    io.vertx.core.Verticle
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractExtension

    public interface Extension
extends io.vertx.core.Verticle
    If you are unsure if you need to implement this interface, you probably want AbstractExtension instead.

    An extension is like a "plugin" of sorts - basically, it gives a standardized way to provide extra functionality on top of catnip that is *not* user-level application code. An example of this is providing a command library of some sort. Your library code would be implemented as an extension that an end-user could then optionally load in.

    Note that this class extends Verticle. This is because extensions are expected to be deployed as vert.x verticles. A proper catnip implementation will keep track of these deployments to allow unloading or reloading extensions at runtime. Since this class extends Verticle, the easiest way for a custom extension to be "compliant" is to simply extend AbstractExtension, which itself extends AbstractVerticle, as well as implementing this interface.

    Extensions are deployed as vert.x verticles. vert.x provides two lifecycle hooks - Verticle.start(Future) and Verticle.stop(Future) - that should be used for managing an extension's lifecycle. This is not, say, a Bukkit server, and as such, there is no need for lifecycle hooks like preload or unload or similar to be provided. It is possible that this may change in a future catnip update, but is currently unlikely. Note that AbstractVerticle.start() and AbstractVerticle.stop() are provided as convenience methods for when a Future is not needed, and will automatically be available if implementations are based off of AbstractExtension or AbstractVerticle.

    Note that the lifecycle callbacks are called SYNCHRONOUSLY by vert.x, and as such you should take care to not block the event loop in those callbacks!

      • catnip

        Extension catnip(@Nonnull
                 Catnip catnip)
        Inject a catnip instance into this extension. This should be the same as the catnip version that is deploying this extension, and must not be null. A proper extension manager implementation will call this method to inject a catnip instance BEFORE deploying the extension, ie. Verticle.start(Future) / AbstractVerticle.start() will be called AFTER this method.
        Parameters:
        catnip - The catnip instance to inject. May not be null.
